hints_latex:
Recall that

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle{}M^{-1}M=I.
\end{align*}

How can this help us simplify $\displaystyle {}A^k$?

sols_latex:
From
{part
(c)}, we have that $\displaystyle A = MDM^{-1}$ where

\begin{align*}
M = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
-1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\begin{align*}
M^{-1}=\begin{bmatrix}
1/2  &  -1/2\\
1/2  &  1/2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}
D = \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 5
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

Taking powers yields

\begin{align*}
A^{k} &= (MDM^{-1})^k \\
&= MDM^{-1} \cdot MDM^{-1}\cdot \ldots \cdot MDM^{-1} \\
&= MD^{k}M^{-1} \\
&= \begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1 \\
-1 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 0 \\
0 & 5^{k}
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
1/2 & -1/2 \\
1/2 & 1/2
\end{bmatrix} \\
&= \left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\begin{bmatrix}
1 +5^{k} & -1 + 5^{k} \\
-1 +5^{k} & 1 + 5^{k}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

